## Primary diagnosis  
**Osteochondral lesion of the talus of the right ankle (Osteochondral lesion of the talus, OLT)**

---

## Basis for diagnosis  

### 1) Characteristics of medical history  
- **Repeated swelling and pain in the right ankle for 8 years**, the pain has worsened significantly in the past six months**, and **does not relieve after rest**, accompanied by **swelling and obvious limitation of movement**;  
- Conservative treatment is ineffective, in line with the common chronic protracted and progressive clinical course of osteochondral lesions/osteochondral injuries.

### 2) Physical examination showed that the medial ankle joint lesions were the main lesions  
- **Mild tenderness in front of and around the medial ankle** (suggesting that the lesion is more biased towards the medial weight-bearing area of the ankle joint, commonly seen in osteochondral injury on the medial side of the talus trochlea);  
- Ankle dorsal extension and plantar flexion **mild limitation**, which corresponds to the limitation of movement caused by intra-articular lesions;  
- **Negative ankle instability-related test** (ADT-, varus stress test-), which does not support lateral collateral ligament injury/ankle instability as the main cause;  
- Negative anterior/posterior impingement test, which does not support the primary diagnosis of ankle impingement syndrome alone.

### 3) MRI imaging basis (combined with typical manifestations of the images shown)  
- Focal osteochondral abnormalities signal under the talus trochlear articular surface as a subchondral bone marrow edema-like change and signs of discontinuity/defect or exfoliation of the osteochondral plane (consistent with MRI features of OLT);  
- The imaging findings are consistent with the patient's long-term ankle pain, swelling, and limited mobility.

> If you can supplement other aspects of the MRI (coronal/axonal) or report text (whether free bodies, cartilage cap integrity, lesion size and staging) can be further recommended for more precise classification/staging and treatment.

## Primary diagnosis  
**Chronic strain partial tear of the common extensor tendon of the right elbow (lateral epicondylitis/tennis elbow)**

---

## Basis for diagnosis  

### 1) Characteristics of medical history  
- recurrent pain in the right elbow (8-year course), which worsens in the last 6 months with limited mobility;  
- There are no signs of systemic infection/tuberculosis such as chills, fever, night sweats, and no nerve compression manifestations such as numbness at the distal limbs, which is more in line with **chronic degeneration/strain injury**.

### 2) Physical examination  
- **Tenderness in the lateral epicondyle of the humerus is obvious**: the pain is localized in the area of the attachment point of the common extensor tendon;  
- **Mill sign positive**: It indicates pulling pain in the common extensor tendon (especially the extensor carpi radialis brevis muscle, etc.), which is a typical sign of lateral epicondylitis;  
- Negative elbow varus stress test: does not support obvious collateral ligament instability;  
- Normal muscle strength, normal distal sensory circulation: does not support significant neurovascular injury.

### 3) Imaging (MRI) support points (combined with typical meaning of the images shown)  
- Abnormal signals in the soft tissue/tendon attachment area on the lateral side of the elbow (near the lateral epicondyle of the humerus) (often manifested as T2/lipid-inhibiting sequence hyperintensity, uneven tendon structure, and impaired focal fiber continuity), which conforms to the imaging characteristics of **degeneration of the common tendon attachment point of the extensor muscle with partial fiber tear**;  
- No signs suggestive of acute fracture dislocation (combined with signs and analyses are not consistent with acute trauma).

> In summary, pain localization (lateral epicondyle) + positive Mill sign + MRI showed degeneration/partial tear in the attachment area of the common extensor tendon, which was most consistent with "chronic exertion partial tear of the common extensor tendon of the right elbow (lateral epicondylitis)".

## Primary diagnosis  
**Chronic partial tear/tendinopathy (lateral epicondylitis, tennis elbow) of the common extensor tendon of the left elbow (lateral epicondylitis, tennis elbow)**

---

## Basis for diagnosis  

### 1) Characteristics of medical history  
- **Lateral condyle pain in the left elbow** recurrent **>1 year**;  
- Pain worsens with **forearm movement/exertion** and relieves after braking;  
- Previous occlusive therapy can be relieved but is prone to recurrence, suggesting **chronic strain tendon attachment lesions**, and conservative treatment is not effective.

### 2) Positive signs on physical examination (localized at the origin of the lateral extensor tendon)  
- **Significant tenderness in the lateral condyle of the left elbow**;  
- **Positive Mills test** (extensor muscle group induces lateral epicondylar pain);  
- **Positive resistance to wrist extension and finger extension test** (the origin of the common tendon of the extensor muscle that stimulates the excitation);  
- The elbow joint mobility is basically normal, the muscle strength and sensory circulation are normal, which is more in line with **tendon attachment/tendon injury** rather than severe damage to the intra-articular structure.

### 3) Imaging (MRI) support  
- MRI showed abnormal signal manifestations in the common tendon attachment area of the extensor muscle near the lateral epicondyle of the humerus (consistent with the imaging features of tendinopathy/partial fiber tear), consistent with clinical sign localization.

> Note: You provide a single MRI screenshot, which cannot describe all signs (e.g., tendon thickening, T2 hyperintensity, extent and extent of perienthesion edema, etc.) like a complete sequence, but combined with typical medical history and physical examination, the most consistent primary diagnosis is the above-mentioned "chronic partial tear/tendinopathy (lateral epicondylitis) at the common tendon attachment of the extensor muscle of the left elbow".

